 {"id":"asupersync-3qv04.7.4","title":"[WASM][Packages] Restore root pnpm workspace manifest required by release tooling","description":"Browser Edition release tooling already assumes a root package.json exists, but the repo currently only has pnpm-workspace.yaml/.npmrc/tsconfig.base.json. This breaks scripts/validate_package_build.sh, scripts/validate_npm_pack_smoke.sh, publish.yml corepack activation (node -p require('./package.json').packageManager), and root-manifest contract tests. Restore a minimal root pnpm workspace manifest that matches the existing package topology and validation contracts without inventing a new JS build shape.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Root package.json exists at the repo root and is private.\\n2. Root manifest pins pnpm via packageManager and declares node/pnpm engines.\\n3. Root scripts build/build:wasm/build:packages/typecheck/clean/validate exist and delegate to the established Browser Edition workflow.\\n4. scripts/validate_package_build.sh and scripts/validate_npm_pack_smoke.sh pass against the live workspace.\\n5. Targeted wasm package contract tests pass via rch-backed cargo commands.","notes":"2026-03-09 AmberHarbor: created from archaeology after finding that release tooling and contract tests already require a root workspace manifest, but the file was absent in the working tree. Implemented a minimal root package.json aligned to the existing Browser Edition package topology and validation scripts. Validation status: bash scripts/validate_package_build.sh = PASS; bash scripts/validate_npm_pack_smoke.sh = PASS. rch exec -- cargo test -p asupersync --test wasm_package_build_contract -- --nocapture and rch exec -- cargo test -p asupersync --test wasm_npm_pack_smoke_contract -- --nocapture are both currently blocked by an unrelated compile error in src/web/middleware.rs (non-item in item list around line 317), so I left this bead in_progress instead of closing it prematurely.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","assignee":"AmberHarbor","created_at":"2026-03-09T18:51:24.532334591Z","created_by":"AmberHarbor","updated_at":"2026-03-09T19:15:15.671178679Z","closed_at":"2026-03-09T19:15:15.671152641Z","close_reason":"Superseded after verifying root package.json already existed in HEAD; the real bounded QA improvement was tracked separately.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-3qv04.7.4","depends_on_id":"asupersync-3qv04.7","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-09T18:51:24.532334591Z","created_by":"AmberHarbor"}]}
-{"id":"asupersync-3qv04.8","title":"[WASM] Quality spine: unit coverage, E2E harnesses, and failure forensics","description":"Make test coverage, end-to-end verification, and failure forensics explicit first-class work rather than assuming they will emerge organically from implementation. This track exists because a usable JS/TS/WASM library needs more than green builds: it needs proofs that package entrypoints, ABI handles, browser host bridges, React/Next adapters, and unsupported-environment behavior all work under deterministic automated tests with logs rich enough to debug real failures quickly.\n\nThis track is intentionally cross-cutting. It captures the unit/integration/E2E pyramid, the harness scripts that exercise packaged artifacts, the logging/retention rules for browser failures, and the CI entrypoints that make the evidence reproducible for future agents and humans.","status":"in_progress","priority":3,"issue_type":"epic","estimated_minutes":1440,"created_at":"2026-03-06T15:13:43.008592599Z","created_by":"CopperForest","updated_at":"2026-03-08T18:40:55.561079302Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["diagnostics","qa","testing","wasm"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-3qv04.8","depends_on_id":"asupersync-3qv04","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-06T15:13:43.008592599Z","created_by":"CopperForest","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
